geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\ndocs/milestones.md:130:* surface-localized inputs on explicit T4/T5 morphology regions  \ndocs/milestones.md:131:* surface propagation over a morphology graph  \ndocs/milestones.md:133:* a shared downstream readout so comparison to baselines stays fair\ndocs/milestones.md:140:* a decoder or readout unavailable to the baselines  \ndocs/milestones.md:141:* hand-fitted per-synapse delays granted only to the surface model\ndocs/milestones.md:145:* **`P0`**: canonical point baseline using passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons matched to the same circuit and readout  \ndocs/milestones.md:146:* **`P1`**: stronger reduced baseline using an effective-point or reduced-compartment model with explicit synaptic integration current or explicit delay structure\ndocs/milestones.md:151: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\ndocs/milestones.md:153:**What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?**  \ndocs/milestones.md:154: It should add distributed, morphology-bound intraneuronal state and nothing else that can trivially explain the result.\ndocs/milestones.md:156:**What observable will convince you that the surface model matters?**  \ndocs/milestones.md:167:* **Secondary shared readout:** direction selectivity index\ndocs/milestones.md:171:* **Weak:** the surface model shows propagation or spread that the point model cannot show by construction  \ndocs/milestones.md:172:* **Moderate:** the surface model changes a shared readout such as null-direction suppression, latency, or DSI  \ndocs/milestones.md:173:* **Strong:** the shared-readout change shrinks or disappears when morphology or synapse topology is shuf